[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "text": "ResNet Skip Connections. Let's see how gradient flow works during backpropagation.",
    "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-D",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "text": "First, we have a neural network with multiple layers. Data flows forward through the network.",
    "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-D",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 3,
    "text": "Now here comes the key innovation: skip connections. These allow the input to bypass certain layers entirely.",
    "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-D",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "text": "During backpropagation, gradients flow backward. Through regular layers, they become weak and vanish.",
    "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-D",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 5,
    "text": "But through skip connections, gradients maintain their strength and flow directly backward.",
    "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-D",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 6,
    "text": "Without skip connections, gradients vanish through many layers. With skip connections, gradients flow directly, solving the vanishing gradient problem.",
    "voice": "en-US-Wavenet-D",
    "speed": 1.0
  }
]
